Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.650 --> 00:00:04.713
Prof: So we're talking
now about mortgages and how to

00:00:04.713 --> 00:00:08.724
value them,
and if you remember now a

00:00:08.724 --> 00:00:12.022
mortgage--
so the first mortgages,

00:00:12.022 --> 00:00:14.339
by the way,
that we know of,

00:00:14.339 --> 00:00:16.560
come from Babylonian times.
 

00:00:16.560 --> 00:00:19.862
It's not like some American
invented the mortgage or

00:00:19.862 --> 00:00:20.640
something.
 

00:00:20.640 --> 00:00:26.688
This was 3,500-3,800 years old
and we have on these cuneiform

00:00:26.688 --> 00:00:29.310
tablets these mortgages.
 

00:00:29.310 --> 00:00:35.760
And so the idea of a mortgage
is you make a promise,

00:00:35.760 --> 00:00:37.830
you back your promise with
collateral,

00:00:37.830 --> 00:00:41.041
so if you don't keep the
promise they can take your

00:00:41.041 --> 00:00:43.612
house,
and there's some way of getting

00:00:43.612 --> 00:00:47.470
out of the promise because
everybody knows the collateral,

00:00:47.470 --> 00:00:49.805
you might want to leave the
home, and then you have to have

00:00:49.805 --> 00:00:51.940
some way of dissolving the
promise because the promise

00:00:51.940 --> 00:00:53.430
involves many payments over
time.

00:00:53.430 --> 00:00:56.340
So it's making a promise,
backing it with collateral,

00:00:56.340 --> 00:01:00.011
and finding a way to dissolve
the promise at prearranged terms

00:01:00.011 --> 00:01:02.539
in case you want to end it by
prepaying.

00:01:02.539 --> 00:01:06.608
And that prepaying is called
the refinancing option.

00:01:06.608 --> 00:01:10.088
And because there's a
refinancing option it makes the

00:01:10.088 --> 00:01:12.900
mortgage a much more complicated
thing,

00:01:12.900 --> 00:01:16.188
and a much more interesting
thing, and something that,

00:01:16.188 --> 00:01:18.805
for example,
a hedge fund could imagine that

00:01:18.805 --> 00:01:20.629
it could make money trading.
 

00:01:20.629 --> 00:01:23.796
So I just want to give you a
slight indication of how that

00:01:23.796 --> 00:01:24.629
could happen.
 

00:01:24.629 --> 00:01:27.950
So as we said if you have a
typical mortgage,

00:01:27.950 --> 00:01:30.799
say the mortgage rate is 8
percent--

00:01:30.799 --> 00:01:32.970
maybe this is a different
answer than I did--

00:01:32.970 --> 00:01:36.864
so here we have an 8 percent
mortgage with a 6 percent

00:01:36.864 --> 00:01:39.069
interest rate to begin with.
 

00:01:39.069 --> 00:01:42.325
Now, if it's an 8 percent
mortgage the guy's going to have

00:01:42.325 --> 00:01:45.810
to pay much more than 8 percent
a year because a mortgage,

00:01:45.810 --> 00:01:46.920
remember, there are level
payments.

00:01:46.920 --> 00:01:48.560
We're talking about fixed rate
mortgages.

00:01:48.560 --> 00:01:51.769
You pay the same amount every
single year for 30 years,

00:01:51.769 --> 00:01:54.433
now you're really paying
monthly and I've ignored the

00:01:54.433 --> 00:01:57.455
monthly business because it's
just too many months and there

00:01:57.455 --> 00:01:58.480
are 360 of them.
 

00:01:58.480 --> 00:02:01.140
So I'm thinking of it as an
annual payment.

00:02:01.140 --> 00:02:04.108
You have to pay,
of course, more than 8 dollars

00:02:04.108 --> 00:02:08.044
a year because if the mortgage
rate were 8 percent and you had

00:02:08.044 --> 00:02:12.110
a balloon payment on the end,
you'd pay 8,8, 8,108.

00:02:12.110 --> 00:02:15.280
That's the way they used to
work, but they were changed.

00:02:15.280 --> 00:02:18.972
So you could imagine the old
fashioned mortgage would pay

00:02:18.972 --> 00:02:21.536
8,8, 8,8, 8,108;
if you didn't pay your 8

00:02:21.536 --> 00:02:25.090
somewhere along the line they'd
confiscate your whole house and

00:02:25.090 --> 00:02:28.530
then take what was owed out of
it and you could get out of it

00:02:28.530 --> 00:02:29.620
by paying 100.
 

00:02:29.620 --> 00:02:33.697
The new mortgages instead of
paying 8 every year for 30 years

00:02:33.697 --> 00:02:37.706
you pay 8.88 every year for 30
years because if you discount

00:02:37.706 --> 00:02:41.650
payments of 8.8 for 30 years at
8 percent you get 100.

00:02:41.650 --> 00:02:46.016
So the present value is 100 at
the agreed upon discounting rate

00:02:46.016 --> 00:02:48.060
or mortgage rate 8 percent.
 

00:02:48.060 --> 00:02:52.560
And so you see how important
this discount rate is.

00:02:52.560 --> 00:02:56.043
And the remaining balance,
however, goes down because

00:02:56.043 --> 00:03:00.128
every time you're paying you're
paying more than the 8 percent

00:03:00.128 --> 00:03:01.000
interest.
 

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:06.638
You're paying in the first year
8.8 instead of 8 and so that gap

00:03:06.638 --> 00:03:11.830
of .88 is used to reduce the
balance from 100 to 99.117.

00:03:11.830 --> 00:03:14.838
And so you see the balance is
going down over time and making

00:03:14.838 --> 00:03:17.396
the lender safer and safer
because the same house is

00:03:17.396 --> 00:03:18.150
backing it.
 

00:03:18.150 --> 00:03:20.310
So it's called an amortizing
mortgage.

00:03:20.310 --> 00:03:22.610
Now, why is it difficult to
value?

00:03:22.610 --> 00:03:25.818
Because you have the option,
any time you want,

00:03:25.818 --> 00:03:27.960
and there's a good reason for
that option,

00:03:27.960 --> 00:03:30.711
any time you want you have the
option of getting out of the

00:03:30.711 --> 00:03:33.473
mortgage and just saying,
"Okay, I've paid 3

00:03:33.473 --> 00:03:35.970
payments of 8.88,
I don't want to do it anymore.

00:03:35.970 --> 00:03:41.419
I want to pay off 97.13 and
then let's call it quits."

00:03:41.419 --> 00:03:42.318
And they say,
"Okay,"

00:03:42.318 --> 00:03:43.610
and there's nothing they can do
about it.

00:03:43.610 --> 00:03:46.169
Now, when are you going to
exercise that option?

00:03:46.169 --> 00:03:49.465
You're going to exercise that
option either because you have

00:03:49.465 --> 00:03:51.718
to move,
that's the intention of it,

00:03:51.718 --> 00:03:55.240
or you'll exercise it when it's
most advantageous to you.

00:03:55.240 --> 00:03:58.910
Now, why could it become
advantageous to exercise it?

00:03:58.910 --> 00:04:01.750
Well, you don't really want to
exercise the option and this is

00:04:01.750 --> 00:04:03.800
the way most people think of it
backwards.

00:04:03.800 --> 00:04:05.855
They think, "Oh,
the interest rates are going

00:04:05.855 --> 00:04:06.150
down.
 

00:04:06.150 --> 00:04:08.479
That means I'll get a new
mortgage with a lower interest

00:04:08.479 --> 00:04:09.030
rate."
 

00:04:09.030 --> 00:04:12.038
They're hoping for exactly the
wrong thing.

00:04:12.038 --> 00:04:15.128
If the interest rates go up
what they've got is a much

00:04:15.128 --> 00:04:18.742
better mortgage because they're
continuing to buy at the same 8

00:04:18.742 --> 00:04:21.947
percent interest and maybe
interest rates in the economy

00:04:21.947 --> 00:04:25.620
have become 12 percent and
they're actually making money.

00:04:25.620 --> 00:04:29.980
So people who borrow in times
of high inflation do better.

00:04:29.980 --> 00:04:32.713
When there are times of
deflation the borrowers get

00:04:32.713 --> 00:04:33.259
crushed.
 

00:04:33.259 --> 00:04:36.466
Irving Fisher said one of the
main reasons for the Depression

00:04:36.466 --> 00:04:39.245
being so bad is all the
entrepreneurial people in the

00:04:39.245 --> 00:04:41.141
country,
as usual, were borrowing,

00:04:41.141 --> 00:04:43.740
and then there was a deflation
and so they were getting

00:04:43.740 --> 00:04:44.269
crushed.
 

00:04:44.269 --> 00:04:47.225
And the very people who drive
the economy were being hurt the

00:04:47.225 --> 00:04:47.569
most.
 

00:04:47.569 --> 00:04:50.531
And so that feedback,
he said, was responsible for

00:04:50.531 --> 00:04:53.009
part of the severity of the
Depression.

00:04:53.009 --> 00:04:56.370
So you see interest rates can
go up or down and what happens?

00:04:56.370 --> 00:04:58.819
When they go up,
if they go up high enough to 19

00:04:58.819 --> 00:05:00.540
percent you think,
"My, gosh,

00:05:00.540 --> 00:05:02.939
I've made a fortune holding
this mortgage.

00:05:02.939 --> 00:05:08.136
I'm still borrowing at 8
percent and I can invest my

00:05:08.136 --> 00:05:10.990
money at 19 percent."
 

00:05:10.990 --> 00:05:13.228
So you've made a fortune and
the poor lender's gotten

00:05:13.228 --> 00:05:13.660
crushed.
 

00:05:13.660 --> 00:05:17.170
On the other hand if the
interest rates go way down here,

00:05:17.170 --> 00:05:20.574
so the present value of what
you owe if you kept paying it

00:05:20.574 --> 00:05:23.507
becomes huge,
you don't have to face that big

00:05:23.507 --> 00:05:27.401
loss because you just prepay at
whatever the remaining balance

00:05:27.401 --> 00:05:30.720
is there and then you've
protected your downside.

00:05:30.720 --> 00:05:34.105
So by paying attention and
deciding when the optimal time

00:05:34.105 --> 00:05:36.706
to prepay is,
you can save yourself a lot of

00:05:36.706 --> 00:05:39.790
money and thereby cost the bank
a lot of money.

00:05:39.790 --> 00:05:41.940
So when exactly should you
prepay?

00:05:41.940 --> 00:05:43.730
When should you exercise your
options?

00:05:43.730 --> 00:05:46.149
Well, in this example if you
never exercised it you'd be

00:05:46.149 --> 00:05:47.625
handing the bank,
effectively,

00:05:47.625 --> 00:05:50.206
120 dollars even though they
lent you 20 [correction:

00:05:50.206 --> 00:05:51.050
lent you 100].
 

00:05:51.050 --> 00:05:54.610
So the bank would have made a
20 percent profit on you.

00:05:54.610 --> 00:06:02.716
But if you exercise your option
optimally you're going to make

00:06:02.716 --> 00:06:05.151
not 100--
the bank is not going to get

00:06:05.151 --> 00:06:07.113
100 dollars out of you,
they're going to even get less

00:06:07.113 --> 00:06:07.769
than 100 dollars.
 

00:06:07.769 --> 00:06:09.949
They're going to get 98 dollars
out of you.

00:06:09.949 --> 00:06:14.560
So when exactly should you be
exercising your option?

00:06:14.560 --> 00:06:16.750
Well, we went over this last
time.

00:06:16.750 --> 00:06:18.579
I'll do it once again.
 

00:06:18.579 --> 00:06:23.254
So remember,
the payment you owed was

00:06:23.254 --> 00:06:27.930
8.88,8.88, blah,
blah, blah, 8.88.

00:06:27.930 --> 00:06:34.172
The remaining balance started,
of course, at 100 and then it

00:06:34.172 --> 00:06:40.519
went down to 99.11 and then it
kept going down from there.

00:06:40.519 --> 00:06:44.040
So since I can't remember the
numbers let's just call this

00:06:44.040 --> 00:06:46.254
B_1,
the remaining balance which

00:06:46.254 --> 00:06:49.220
happened to be,
you know, it was 99.11 the

00:06:49.220 --> 00:06:50.250
first time.
 

00:06:50.250 --> 00:06:52.860
Let's call this B_1,
then I went to B_2,

00:06:52.860 --> 00:06:59.110
B_3 etcetera and then
B_30 is equal to 0,

00:06:59.110 --> 00:07:01.379
