00:19:15.950 --> 00:19:17.259
So the banks wouldn't do that.
 

00:19:17.259 --> 00:19:19.109
They would just go out of
business if they did something

00:19:19.109 --> 00:19:19.750
stupid like that.
 

00:19:19.750 --> 00:19:23.265
They wouldn't do that unless
they thought that the homeowners

00:19:23.265 --> 00:19:25.549
weren't acting,
at least not all of them

00:19:25.549 --> 00:19:26.838
acting, optimally.
 

00:19:26.838 --> 00:19:31.582
So suppose you had to predict
how people are going to act in

00:19:31.582 --> 00:19:35.200
the future and you wanted to
trade on that?

00:19:35.200 --> 00:19:38.108
What would you do?
 

00:19:38.108 --> 00:19:40.358
How would you think about
predicting it?

00:19:40.358 --> 00:19:41.750
So this is the data that you
have.

00:19:41.750 --> 00:19:43.950
What would you do?
 

00:19:43.950 --> 00:19:44.710
You have this data.
 

00:19:44.710 --> 00:19:46.048
These are 8 percent things.
 

00:19:46.048 --> 00:19:48.722
You also have 9 percent
mortgages issued the year

00:19:48.722 --> 00:19:50.564
before,
and then maybe a year before

00:19:50.564 --> 00:19:53.180
that there were 8 and 1 half
percent interest and you have

00:19:53.180 --> 00:19:55.040
that history,
and you've got all these

00:19:55.040 --> 00:19:57.338
different pools and all these
different histories.

00:19:57.338 --> 00:20:03.832
How would you think about
figuring out a prepayment--how

00:20:03.832 --> 00:20:07.608
would you predict prepayments?
 

00:20:07.608 --> 00:20:10.882
Well, the way economists,
macro economists at least in

00:20:10.882 --> 00:20:14.327
the old days,
used to make predictions,

00:20:14.327 --> 00:20:17.520
they would say,
"Hum, the first quarter

00:20:17.520 --> 00:20:18.880
looks pretty good."
 

00:20:18.880 --> 00:20:20.450
What are they predicting now?
 

00:20:20.450 --> 00:20:24.058
Now, they're saying
unemployment is probably going

00:20:24.058 --> 00:20:28.183
to keep rising for the next
quarter or two well until the

00:20:28.183 --> 00:20:30.777
next year,
but at that point things are

00:20:30.777 --> 00:20:33.538
going to turn around and we
expect the economy to get

00:20:33.538 --> 00:20:35.991
stronger,
come out of its recession and

00:20:35.991 --> 00:20:39.577
unemployment should gradually
improve from its high which we

00:20:39.577 --> 00:20:43.101
expect will be 10 and 1 half
percent to something back down

00:20:43.101 --> 00:20:45.348
to 6 percent by the end of 2011.
 

00:20:45.348 --> 00:20:47.960
That's more or less the
economists' prediction.

00:20:47.960 --> 00:20:51.490
Now, can you make a prediction
like that about prepayments?

00:20:51.490 --> 00:20:53.480
Would it make sense to make a
prediction about that?

00:20:53.480 --> 00:20:59.460
Why is that an utterly stupid
kind of prediction?

00:20:59.460 --> 00:21:03.940
What is the essence of good
prediction?

00:21:03.940 --> 00:21:06.938
If you wanted to predict
something and you were going to

00:21:06.938 --> 00:21:10.045
lose a lot of money if your
prediction was wrong how would

00:21:10.045 --> 00:21:13.152
you refine your prediction
compared to what I just gave as

00:21:13.152 --> 00:21:14.569
a sample prediction?
 

00:21:14.569 --> 00:21:15.250
Yep?
 

00:21:15.250 --> 00:21:16.682
Student: You have to
have a number of scenarios and

00:21:16.682 --> 00:21:17.311
&gt;
 

00:21:17.311 --> 00:21:17.690
to each one.
 

00:21:17.690 --> 00:21:18.680
Prof: Exactly.
 

00:21:18.680 --> 00:21:22.623
So what he said is if you're
even the slightest bit

00:21:22.623 --> 00:21:27.276
sophisticated you're not going
to make a bald non-contingent

00:21:27.276 --> 00:21:28.460
prediction.
 

00:21:28.460 --> 00:21:30.740
Things are going to get worse
the next two quarters,

00:21:30.740 --> 00:21:32.288
then they're going to start
getting better,

00:21:32.288 --> 00:21:36.917
then things are going to get as
well as they're going to get

00:21:36.917 --> 00:21:38.328
after two years.
 

00:21:38.328 --> 00:21:39.618
You'll solve the problem after
two years.

00:21:39.618 --> 00:21:43.339
What happens if another war
breaks out in Iraq?

00:21:43.339 --> 00:21:45.170
What if Iran bombs Israel?
 

00:21:45.170 --> 00:21:49.750
What if there's another crash
in commercial real estate?

00:21:49.750 --> 00:21:53.009
How could that prediction
possibly turn out to be true?

00:21:53.009 --> 00:21:54.940
It's a sure thing it's going to
be wrong.

00:21:54.940 --> 00:21:57.647
It's just impossible that's
going to be right because the

00:21:57.647 --> 00:22:00.500
guy making the prediction has
made no contingencies built in

00:22:00.500 --> 00:22:01.420
his prediction.
 

00:22:01.420 --> 00:22:03.460
You know that guy's making a
prediction for free.

00:22:03.460 --> 00:22:06.070
Someone may be paying him to
hear him, but he's not going to

00:22:06.070 --> 00:22:07.930
be penalized if his prediction
is wrong.

00:22:07.930 --> 00:22:10.930
No one in their right mind
would make such a prediction.

00:22:10.930 --> 00:22:14.713
So the first thing you should
do in predicting prepayments is

00:22:14.713 --> 00:22:18.308
to realize that you've got a
tree of possible futures,

00:22:18.308 --> 00:22:22.045
and given this tree of possible
futures you're going to predict

00:22:22.045 --> 00:22:25.778
different prepayments depending
on where you go on the tree.

00:22:25.778 --> 00:22:32.113
So you see, prediction is not a
simple one event--it's not a one

00:22:32.113 --> 00:22:33.420
shot thing.
 

00:22:33.420 --> 00:22:37.380
Just as he so aptly put it,
it's a many scenario thing.

00:22:37.380 --> 00:22:40.001
You have to predict on many,
many scenarios what you think

00:22:40.001 --> 00:22:43.038
will happen and that makes your
prediction much better because,

00:22:43.038 --> 00:22:44.848
of course, if there is a war in
Iraq,

00:22:44.848 --> 00:22:46.680
and if there is a catastrophe
in Afghanistan,

00:22:46.680 --> 00:22:49.837
and if Iran does bomb Israel,
and if the commercial real

00:22:49.837 --> 00:22:53.398
estate market collapses things
are going to be a lot worse than

00:22:53.398 --> 00:22:55.410
this original guy's prediction.
 

00:22:55.410 --> 00:22:59.784
So everybody knows that,
so why not make the prediction

00:22:59.784 --> 00:23:01.078
more sensible?
 

00:23:01.078 --> 00:23:06.528
So, on Wall Street that's what
everybody's done for 20 years.

00:23:06.528 --> 00:23:09.140
Now, they haven't done it for
30 years.

00:23:09.140 --> 00:23:12.108
It's just 20 years that they've
been doing that.

00:23:12.108 --> 00:23:18.383
So when I got to Kidder Peabody
in 1990 they were making these

00:23:18.383 --> 00:23:21.160
one scenario predictions.
 

00:23:21.160 --> 00:23:24.598
It's a long story which I'll
tell maybe Sunday night.

00:23:24.598 --> 00:23:27.663
I ended up in charge of the
Research Department and so we

00:23:27.663 --> 00:23:29.962
made, you know,
other firms were doing this

00:23:29.962 --> 00:23:32.588
