out what the prices are of any

00:30:31.124 --> 00:30:32.930
mortgage by backward induction.
 

00:30:32.930 --> 00:30:35.170
So how would you do it again by
backward induction?

00:30:35.170 --> 00:30:36.618
The same we always did it.
 

00:30:36.618 --> 00:30:42.970
Over here, what would you do
over here?

00:30:42.970 --> 00:30:54.068
How would you change this rule?
 

00:30:54.068 --> 00:30:57.509
Well, you would just be feeding
in the prepayment function.

00:30:57.509 --> 00:31:09.190
So what would the prepayment
function be?

00:31:09.190 --> 00:31:11.192
Well, people wouldn't be doing
a minimum here,

00:31:11.192 --> 00:31:11.548
right?
 

00:31:11.548 --> 00:31:13.348
They're not deciding whether or
not to prepay,

00:31:13.348 --> 00:31:14.349
they're just prepaying.
 

00:31:14.349 --> 00:31:18.150
So let's get rid of that.
 

00:31:18.150 --> 00:31:19.690
They're prepaying.
 

00:31:19.690 --> 00:31:24.250
So this is the value of 1
dollars left of principal.

00:31:24.250 --> 00:31:28.065
So some of them are prepaying
and that's the function,

00:31:28.065 --> 00:31:31.880
so prepay, and that depends on
what node you're at.

00:31:31.880 --> 00:31:34.971
And here it says what
percentage of the remaining

00:31:34.971 --> 00:31:36.710
balance is being prepaid.
 

00:31:36.710 --> 00:31:39.558
So that tells you,
that rule, who's prepaying,

00:31:39.558 --> 00:31:43.638
and then with the rest of the
money that's going on until next

00:31:43.638 --> 00:31:51.018
time 1 minus that same thing,
1 minus prepay times exactly

00:31:51.018 --> 00:31:54.759
what we had before.
 

00:31:54.759 --> 00:31:57.999
So this part of 1 dollar got
prepaid immediately so that's

00:31:57.999 --> 00:32:00.500
the cash that went to the
