so they're people.
 

00:38:43.820 --> 00:38:45.170
That's a kind of person.
 

00:38:45.170 --> 00:38:48.331
And suppose you go down here
and you have the people who are

00:38:48.331 --> 00:38:49.510
optimally prepaying?
 

00:38:49.510 --> 00:38:52.512
Suppose you imagine that half
the people were optimally

00:38:52.512 --> 00:38:55.070
prepaying and half the people
never prepaid?

00:38:55.070 --> 00:38:59.630
Well, would that explain this
favorable selection?

00:38:59.630 --> 00:39:02.585
Absolutely it would explain it
because when you went through

00:39:02.585 --> 00:39:04.489
your little tree and you went
here,

00:39:04.489 --> 00:39:09.105
and here, and here,
and here, by the time you got

00:39:09.105 --> 00:39:13.974
down here all those people,
all the optimal pre-payers

00:39:13.974 --> 00:39:15.730
they're all prepaying.
 

00:39:15.730 --> 00:39:18.572
So you start off with
half-optimal guys and

00:39:18.572 --> 00:39:19.860
half-asleep guys.
 

00:39:19.860 --> 00:39:22.592
Once you get down here all the
optimal guys have disappeared

00:39:22.592 --> 00:39:24.539
and the pool that's left is all
asleep,

00:39:24.539 --> 00:39:27.690
so of course the pool is worth
much more here given the

00:39:27.690 --> 00:39:29.909
interest rate than it was over
here.

00:39:29.909 --> 00:39:34.684
In fact, if it goes back then
again to here where it was

00:39:34.684 --> 00:39:37.550
before--sorry that's same line.
 

00:39:37.550 --> 00:39:40.349
If it goes back to here--have I
done this right?

00:39:40.349 --> 00:39:42.630
No, I've got to go back twice
here and then here.

00:39:42.630 --> 00:39:45.532
So once it goes back to here if
it goes here,

00:39:45.532 --> 00:39:49.291
here, here and here then the
pool is going to be much more

00:39:49.291 --> 00:39:51.929
valuable here than it started
there.

00:39:51.929 --> 00:39:54.744
There are half as many people,
but it's worth much more than

00:39:54.744 --> 00:39:56.079
half of what it was there.
 

00:39:56.079 --> 00:40:00.072
So the way to do this is to
break--so then you're looking at

00:40:00.072 --> 00:40:01.289
the individuals.
 

00:40:01.289 --> 00:40:03.838
You're saying one class of
people is very smart,

00:40:03.838 --> 00:40:07.148
or one class of people is very
alert, it's a much better word,

00:40:07.148 --> 00:40:09.210
one class of people is very
alert.

00:40:09.210 --> 00:40:12.010
One class of people is very
un-alert and as you go through

00:40:12.010 --> 00:40:14.909
the tree the alert people are
going to disappear faster than

00:40:14.909 --> 00:40:17.710
the non-alert people and that's
why you're going to have a

00:40:17.710 --> 00:40:20.610
favorable selection of people
who's left in the pool.

00:40:20.610 --> 00:40:24.010
Well, of course,
there are no extremes of

00:40:24.010 --> 00:40:29.112
perfectly rational or perfectly
asleep in the economy so what

00:40:29.112 --> 00:40:33.280
you can do is you can make
people in between.

00:40:33.280 --> 00:40:34.570
How do you make them in between?
 

00:40:34.570 --> 00:40:36.360
Well, suppose that,
for example,

00:40:36.360 --> 00:40:37.690
I only did one thing.
 

00:40:37.690 --> 00:40:40.119
Suppose it's costly to prepay?
 

00:40:40.119 --> 00:40:41.887
Some people just say to
themselves, "I'm going to

00:40:41.887 --> 00:40:43.190
have to take a whole day off of
work.

00:40:43.190 --> 00:40:45.099
I'm not going to write my paper.
 

00:40:45.099 --> 00:40:48.579
I might lose some business that
I was going to do that day.

00:40:48.579 --> 00:40:52.568
A whole bunch of stuff I'm
losing, so I'm going to subtract

00:40:52.568 --> 00:40:53.050
that.
 

00:40:53.050 --> 00:40:54.960
I'm not going to prepay.
 

00:40:54.960 --> 00:40:58.023
I'm not going to even think
about doing it unless I can get

00:40:58.023 --> 00:41:00.929
at least a certain benefit from
having done it."

00:41:00.929 --> 00:41:04.161
So you can add a cost of
prepaying and people aren't

00:41:04.161 --> 00:41:07.835
going to prepay unless the gain
that they have by prepaying

00:41:07.835 --> 00:41:10.750
exceeds the cost of doing the
prepayments.

00:41:10.750 --> 00:41:14.480
So to take the simplest case
let's suppose the very act of--

00:41:14.480 --> 00:41:15.730
never mind the thinking and all
that--

00:41:15.730 --> 00:41:18.983
the very act of prepaying,
going to the bank literally

00:41:18.983 --> 00:41:20.090
costs you money.
 

00:41:20.090 --> 00:41:24.586
So if you have a value,
if the thing is 100 and you can

00:41:24.586 --> 00:41:26.802
prepay,
you know, if you do your

00:41:26.802 --> 00:41:30.202
calculations and don't prepay
today it's worth 98 and if you

00:41:30.202 --> 00:41:33.373
prepay today the remaining
balance is 94 you're saving 4

00:41:33.373 --> 00:41:35.664
dollars,
but if the cost of prepayment

00:41:35.664 --> 00:41:37.610
is 5 you're still not going to
do it.

00:41:37.610 --> 00:41:39.766
So you get a guy with a high
cost of prepaying,

00:41:39.766 --> 00:41:42.485
an infinite cost of prepaying,
he's going to look like he's

00:41:42.485 --> 00:41:43.469
totally un-alert.
 

00:41:43.469 --> 00:41:46.130
A guy with zero cost of paying
is going to look like he's

00:41:46.130 --> 00:41:46.889
totally alert.
 

00:41:46.889 --> 00:41:51.594
So you can have gradations of
rationality, and you can have

00:41:51.594 --> 00:41:53.460
different dimensions.
 

00:41:53.460 --> 00:41:58.447
So you can have cost of
prepaying and you can have

00:41:58.447 --> 00:41:59.670
alertness.
 

00:41:59.670 --> 00:42:03.246
What's the percentage of time
you're actually paying attention

00:42:03.246 --> 00:42:04.010
that month?
 

00:42:04.010 --> 00:42:06.760
What fraction of the months do
you actually pay attention,

00:42:06.760 --> 00:42:09.704
and you can have a distribution
of people, different costs and

00:42:09.704 --> 00:42:10.960
different alertnesses.
 

00:42:10.960 --> 00:42:14.269
So that's the model that I
built.

00:42:14.269 --> 00:42:16.380
It's a simplified form of it.
 

00:42:16.380 --> 00:42:18.409
It gives you an idea.
 

00:42:18.409 --> 00:42:23.278
So here's this burnout effect
that I showed that if you take

00:42:23.278 --> 00:42:26.625
the same coupons,
but an older one rather than

00:42:26.625 --> 00:42:30.380
a--an older one that's burned
out will always prepay slower,

00:42:30.380 --> 00:42:33.931
so the pink one is always less
than the blue one because it

00:42:33.931 --> 00:42:36.380
went through an opportunity to
prepay.

00:42:36.380 --> 00:42:39.961
So here you start with a pool
of guys on the right,

00:42:39.961 --> 00:42:43.757
and then after a while,
after time has gone down a lot

00:42:43.757 --> 00:42:45.550
of them have prepaid.
 

00:42:45.550 --> 00:42:48.050
So here's alertness and cost.
 

00:42:48.050 --> 00:42:53.154
So you describe a person by
what his cost of prepaying is

00:42:53.154 --> 00:42:55.159
and how alert he is.
 

00:42:55.159 --> 00:42:57.704
The more alert he is and the
lower the cost of prepaying the

00:42:57.704 --> 00:42:58.869
closer to rational he is.
 

00:42:58.869 --> 00:43:01.601
The less alert he is,
the higher the cost of

00:43:01.601 --> 00:43:04.969
prepaying the closer to the
totally dumb guy he is.

00:43:04.969 --> 00:43:07.945
And so you could have a whole
normally distributed

00:43:07.945 --> 00:43:11.650
distribution of people and over
time those groups are going to

00:43:11.650 --> 00:43:14.809
be reduced because a lot of them
are prepaying,

00:43:14.809 --> 00:43:17.110
but they won't be reduce
symmetrically.

00:43:17.110 --> 00:43:20.547
The low cost high alertness
guys are going to disappear much

00:43:20.547 --> 00:43:24.043
faster and the pool's going to
get more and more favorable to

00:43:24.043 --> 00:43:24.510
you.
 

00:43:24.510 --> 00:43:28.213
And so anyway,
all you have to do is

00:43:28.213 --> 00:43:32.226
parameterize the cost,
what the distribution of people

00:43:32.226 --> 00:43:35.255
in the population,
what the standard deviation and

00:43:35.255 --> 00:43:38.369
expectation of cost is and of
alertness is,

00:43:38.369 --> 00:43:40.550
and that tells you what this
distribution looks like.

00:43:40.550 --> 00:43:43.376
So you're fitting four numbers
and you've got thousands of

00:43:43.376 --> 00:43:45.610
pools and hundreds and hundreds
of months,

00:43:45.610 --> 00:43:50.519
and fitting four parameters you
can end up fitting all the data.

00:43:50.519 --> 00:43:52.019
So look at what happens here.
 

00:43:52.019 --> 00:43:53.780
So here's the same data.
 

00:43:53.780 --> 00:43:57.539
So I just tell you I know that
in a population,

00:43:57.539 --> 00:44:01.929
given what I've calculated in
the '90s there,

00:44:01.929 --> 00:44:04.820
I know what fraction of the
people have this cost and that

00:44:04.820 --> 00:44:07.269
alertness,
what fraction of the people are

00:44:07.269 --> 00:44:10.679
so close to dumb that their
costs are astronomical and their

00:44:10.679 --> 00:44:13.882
alertness is tiny,
what fraction of the people

00:44:13.882 --> 00:44:17.320
have almost no cost and a very
high alertness,

00:44:17.320 --> 00:44:19.518
so I'm only estimating four
parameters because I'm assuming

00:44:19.518 --> 00:44:20.579
it's normally distributed.
 

00:44:20.579 --> 00:44:24.554
Given that fixed pool of people
I apply that to the beginning of

00:44:24.554 --> 00:44:28.527
every single mortgage and I just
crank out what would those guys

00:44:28.527 --> 00:44:28.969
do.
 

00:44:28.969 --> 00:44:32.268
In the tree if they knew what
the volatilities were when would

00:44:32.268 --> 00:44:35.210
they decide to prepay,
and then I have to follow a

00:44:35.210 --> 00:44:37.510
scenario out in the future and I
say,

00:44:37.510 --> 00:44:40.228
"Well, along this path
which guy would prepay and which

00:44:40.228 --> 00:44:42.992
guy wouldn't prepay and what
would the total prepayments look

00:44:42.992 --> 00:44:44.190
along that path?"
 

00:44:44.190 --> 00:44:47.130
And so this has generated the
pink line from the model with no

00:44:47.130 --> 00:44:50.021
knowledge of the world except I
fit those parameters and look

00:44:50.021 --> 00:44:52.239
how close it is to what actually
happened.

00:44:52.239 --> 00:44:57.329
So it turns out that it was
incredibly easy to predict,

00:44:57.329 --> 00:45:00.773
contingently predict what
prepayments were going to be and

00:45:00.773 --> 00:45:03.309
therefore to be able to value
mortgages.

00:45:03.309 --> 00:45:05.389
And this was a secret that not
many people,

00:45:05.389 --> 00:45:06.789
you know, a bunch of people
understood,

00:45:06.789 --> 00:45:09.472
but not that many understood,
and so for years we were

00:45:09.472 --> 00:45:12.699
trading at our hedge fund,
first at Kidder and then at

00:45:12.699 --> 00:45:16.027
Ellington with this ability to
contingently forecast

00:45:16.027 --> 00:45:18.309
prepayments at a very high rate.
 

00:45:18.309 --> 00:45:21.005
And why was it so stable,
the prediction,

00:45:21.005 --> 00:45:22.219
and so reliable?
 

00:45:22.219 --> 00:45:24.882
It's because the class of
people stayed pretty much the

00:45:24.882 --> 00:45:27.791
same and every year there'd be
the same kinds of people with

00:45:27.791 --> 00:45:29.320
the same kinds of behavior.
 

00:45:29.320 --> 00:45:30.320
Some were very alert.
 

00:45:30.320 --> 00:45:33.065
Some were very not alert,
but the distribution of types

00:45:33.065 --> 00:45:36.016
was more or less the same and
you could predict with pretty

00:45:36.016 --> 00:45:39.119
good accuracy what was going to
happen from year to year.

00:45:39.119 --> 00:45:42.876
Of course, then after 2003 or
so the class of people started

00:45:42.876 --> 00:45:46.253
to radically change and many
more people who never got

00:45:46.253 --> 00:45:50.137
mortgages before got them and it
became much harder to predict

00:45:50.137 --> 00:45:52.239
what they were going to do.
 

00:45:52.239 --> 00:45:54.570
But so in the old days it was
pretty easy to predict.

00:45:54.570 --> 00:45:55.989
And why was it so easy to
predict?

00:45:55.989 --> 00:46:03.090
Because it was an agent based
model, agent based.

00:46:03.090 --> 00:46:05.427
So, by the way,
I added this volatility here,

00:46:05.427 --> 00:46:08.400
so these guys who just ran
regressions they had to have a

00:46:08.400 --> 00:46:10.420
