parameter.

00:46:10.420 --> 00:46:14.480
So you see as volatility goes
up the prepayments are slower.

00:46:14.480 --> 00:46:17.621
Well, they just had to notice
that and build it right into

00:46:17.621 --> 00:46:18.559
their function.
 

00:46:18.559 --> 00:46:20.539
I didn't even have to think of
that or burnout.

00:46:20.539 --> 00:46:23.927
None of those things did I have
to think about because if you're

00:46:23.927 --> 00:46:26.510
a guy optimizing here and
volatility goes up,

00:46:26.510 --> 00:46:29.695
so you reset the tree so that
the interest rates can change

00:46:29.695 --> 00:46:30.190
faster.
 

00:46:30.190 --> 00:46:32.949
The option is worth more so
you're going to wait longer.

00:46:32.949 --> 00:46:34.961
You're not going to just
exercise it right away because

00:46:34.961 --> 00:46:37.161
you've got a chance that prices
will really go up so you can

00:46:37.161 --> 00:46:39.460
wait a little longer,
afford to wait longer.

00:46:39.460 --> 00:46:41.550
So prepayments will slow down.
 

00:46:41.550 --> 00:46:43.389
So all I'm saying,
all of this is just to say that

00:46:43.389 --> 00:46:47.353
if you have the right--
so it's agent based,

00:46:47.353 --> 00:46:53.527
it's contingent predictions,
those two things together

00:46:53.527 --> 00:46:57.065
enable you to make quite
reliable predictions about the

00:46:57.065 --> 00:46:59.949
future if you're in a stable
environment.

00:46:59.949 --> 00:47:04.085
And so what seems like a
bewildering amount of stuff

00:47:04.085 --> 00:47:07.409
turns out to be pretty easy to
explain.

00:47:07.409 --> 00:47:11.039
So now what happens?
 

